o trade, travel, warfare, humanitarian rescue, recreation, and managing sea level rise. Interleaving ethnographic chapters with reflections on waves in mythology, surf culture, feminist theory, film, Indigenous Pacific activisms, Black Atlantic history, cosmology, and more, Helmreich demonstrates how waves mark out the wakes and breaks of social histories and futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman ecology. 0aOcean and civilization. 0aOcean wavesxClimatic factors. 0aOceanxPhilosophy. 0aSea levelxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aFoster, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReichman, Daniel R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024538?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024538423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024538/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles